(100315, 'Yehia', 'HOURY', 'Mr', '', '30', 'ma', '', '', 'yehia@flat6labs.com', 'Flat6Labs Tunisia', 'Yehia is Managing Director at Flat6Labs Tunisia, a regional startup accelerator and VC fund. Prior to Flat6Labs, Yehia was leading tech-driven initiatives for youth employability and entrepreneurship at a regional organization working across the MENA region. Throughout his career, he held various roles in non-governmental, research, and multilateral organizations in Africa and Asia before joining the World Bank in their Microfinance division. As an Acumen Fund Fellow, he advised a large-scale health-tech company in India and managed technology and business strategy at a startup based in Jordan. Yehia holds a BSc in Computer Science from McGill University in Canada and a Masters in International Affairs from Columbia University in New York.\r\n', 22, 2, 1, 1),
(100316, 'Essma', 'BEN HAMIDA', 'Mme', '', '3', 'tn', '', '', 'essma.benhamida@endatamweel.tn', 'Enda inter-arabe', 'Essma Ben Hamida: Development activist. Born in Tunisia. Degree in geography and history and one post-graduate year in urban planning (Paris). Began career as a secondary school teacher and a TV journalist/reporter in Tunisia. Opened the first bureau of the Tunisian Press Agency, TAP, in New York at the United Nations. 1981-1989, opened the Rome bureau of the International Foundation for Development Alternatives (IFDA) and worked as a senior journalist with the Third World Press agency, Inter-Press Service, (Rome and Geneva). \r\nHas worked as a consultant for various UN agencies. CGAP/Sanabel certified trainer.\r\nCo-founded, with michael cracknell, enda inter-arabe, an international NGO to contribute to the development of the disadvantaged women and men in Tunisia. \r\nIn 1995, launched the first best practice microfinance institution in Tunisia. 340 000 active clients, 70% women, $270 million outstanding portfolio, 88 branches, 1800 staff. As of today she resigned from her position as CEO of enda tamweel to manage the NGO enda inter arabe. \r\n\r\nFounding member of Sanabel, the microfinance network in the Arab countries. Elected twice to Sanabel', 8, 2, 1, 1),
